PROJECT
RESEARCH AND APPLICATION OF COMPOSITE MATERIALS IN METAMATERIALS TO ENHANCE ELECTROMAGNETIC WAVE ABSORPTION AND INTERFERENCE SHIELDING FOR TELECOMMUNICATION DEVICES
Good morning/afternoon, professors and fellow students. Welcome to my presentation on my research experience at Le Quy Don Technical University. Today, I am excited to share the entire journey of my hands-on research: from 3D electromagnetic simulation optimization (using CST Studio Suite) to the manual mixing and molding of composite material samples, aiming to shield and control electromagnetic waves for telecommunication systems, aerospace engineering, and high-tech applications.
1. Practical Motivation
My project stems from practical research on improving the electronic circuitry for Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs/Drones) used in search and rescue missions. On a modern drone, numerous electronic and magnetic components are integrated into an extremely compact space—ranging from GPS modules, cameras for live image transmission, and remote control circuits, to data processing chips for motion tracking. During testing, I noticed a critical technical challenge: Electromagnetic Interference (EMI). When brushless motors operate at high power, combined with continuous high-frequency video transmission, they generate a massive amount of parasitic electromagnetic interference. This interference repeatedly bounces off the metal or plastic housing, reflecting directly back into the internal circuitry. This degrades GPS positioning sensor signals, causing processing circuit errors and a total loss of device control.
To address this issue, under the guidance of my professors at Le Quy Don Technical University, I participated in a research branch: fabricating ultra-thin metamaterial shielding layers. These lightweight, thin materials can be applied directly to electronic component housings to absorb interference efficiently. In this project, I was responsible for 3D electromagnetic simulation optimization using CST Studio Suite and the direct fabrication of test samples in the laboratory.
2. Research Content and Process
Step 1: Theoretical Research – The "Trapping" Mechanism of Electromagnetic Waves Using Nano-Absorbent Materials
An electromagnetic wave consists of two inseparable components: the electric field and the magnetic field. To prevent these interfering waves from reflecting and damaging internal circuits, our shielding layer must act like an electromagnetic "black hole"—simultaneously trapping and entirely converting their energy into heat. To achieve this, our research team combined three core components into a smart composite material:
The first component is a dual-index semiconducting material combined with Carbon. These nanostructures capture the electric field component of electromagnetic waves through electric dipole polarization.
The second component consists of Ferrite nano-particles, which handle the magnetic field component through magnetic hysteresis loss, thereby eliminating high-energy interference.
When combined, these materials create a special effect known as interfacial polarization, or the Wagner-Maxwell effect. As electromagnetic waves penetrate this composite material, they continuously interact with the internal microscopic structures, triggering multiple reflection and scattering processes. With each interaction, the energy of the electromagnetic wave is attenuated, partially converted into heat energy, and ultimately fully dissipated.
Step 2: Sample Fabrication in the Laboratory
Mastering the core theory, I proceeded with the molding process for the experimental samples.
First, I prepared the binder matrix. In the lab, I used paraffin (a specialized wax used in electronics measurements). This material offers low cost, a low melting point, and is completely "neutral" (meaning it does not alter the intrinsic electromagnetic properties of the core materials).
Next was the liquefaction phase. The paraffin was placed in small cups and gently heated on an electric stove for about 1 minute to transition from a solid state to a clear, translucent gel.
Then came the powder-mixing phase. The composite powders were weighed according to specific mass ratios (tested at 20%, 30%, and 40% by weight), poured into the gel cup, and stirred thoroughly to ensure uniform dispersion of the nanoparticles.
Finally, the compression molding phase: The mixture was poured into a toroidal (donut-shaped) mold and placed under a hydraulic press. Under high pressure, the solid material was compacted into a firm toroidal ring with dimensions matching the electromagnetic wave coaxial waveguide guide lines.
Step 3: Measuring and Calculating Electromagnetic Parameters
After obtaining the physical samples, I measured the scattering parameters (S-parameters: reflection and transmission coefficients) using a Vector Network Analyzer (VNA). From the measured data, I applied the NRW (Nicolson-Ross-Weir) algorithm to calculate and extract the two core properties of the material: relative permittivity (epsilon_r), related to electric field interaction and absorption, and relative permeability (mu_r), related to magnetic field interaction and dissipation. Accurately determining these parameters is a mandatory step to feed input data into the next simulation phase.
Step 4: Metamaterial Simulation Design Using CST Software
Drones often operate across wide frequency bands (from low-frequency remote control signals to high-speed digital video streaming over WiFi/5G). If a regular material layer is used, the absorption efficiency is insufficient. Therefore, our team upgraded this material layer into a Metamaterial structure, featuring a split-ring resonator (SRR) pattern on the surface. I utilized CST Studio Suite to build a 3D model of this structure, importing the actual permittivity and permeability parameters measured in Step 3. I then simulated the structure across a wide frequency spectrum from 2 GHz to 18 GHz to analyze the optimized data and determine the exact dimensions of the concentric rings, as well as the ideal material thickness for maximum wave cancellation.
Step 5: Comparison, Cross-checking of Results, and Performance Evaluation
The results from the physical sample fabrication and the computer-based simulation showed a very high correlation, proving the outstanding superiority of the metamaterial structure. The material demonstrated strong electromagnetic wave absorption across a wide frequency band from 2 GHz to 18 GHz, while eliminating and dissipating over 99.9% of the reflected wave energy compared to conventional metal housings. As a result, electromagnetic interference no longer reflects back to affect the drone's circuitry and control systems. Instead, it is safely absorbed, scattered, or converted into heat energy within the material's structural matrix.
3. Scientific Contributions
Throughout this journey, the most meaningful milestone for me was that the experimental molding results, the NRW mathematical calculations, and the CST simulation models all yielded highly consistent data, aligning perfectly with my advisors' theoretical guidance. These results not only validate the feasibility of the research model but have also been integrated into a research paper submitted to a peer-reviewed journal.
4. Practical Significance and Conclusion
This research has contributed to the materialization of an ultra-thin, lightweight, yet highly efficient EMI shielding solution, significantly reducing signal loss and positioning errors on search-and-rescue drones. Beyond UAV applications, this metamaterial structure holds vast potential for protecting 5G and 6G microelectronic circuits, highly sensitive medical equipment like MRI or CT scanners, as well as advanced electromagnetic wave control and processing technologies in the future.
